		<h2>Summary</h2>
		<ul>
			<li>Requested in <span class="info">10</span>/<span class="info">26</span> calls</li>
			<li>Requested in <span class="info">6</span>/<span class="info">19</span> pure calls (<a href="../sle2008/index.html#cfp">2008</a>–<a href="../sle2013/index.html#cfp">2013</a> with the longest streak of <span class="info">6</span> years)</li>

			<li>Primary tagged in <span class="info">0</span>/<span class="info">26</span> paper bundles</li>
			<li>Primary tagged in <span class="info">0</span>/<span class="info">19</span> pure proceedings</li>

			<li>Secondary tagged in <span class="info">8</span>/<span class="info">26</span> paper bundles</li>
			<li>Secondary tagged in <span class="info">6</span>/<span class="info">19</span> pure proceedings (<a href="../sle2009/index.html#lop">2009</a>–<a href="../sle2020/index.html#lop">2020</a> with the longest streak of <span class="info">2</span> years)</li>
			<li>Top 3 co-occurring topics:
				<ul>
					<li><a href="t5b.html"><span class="tagL">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a> (<span class="info">3</span> times)</li>
					<li><a href="t2b.html"><span class="tagL">T2B: Evolution</span></a> (<span class="info">2</span> times)</li>
					<li><a href="t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a> (<span class="info">2</span> times)</li>
				</ul>
<li>Top 3 contributors:
				<ul>
					<li><a href="../profile/GuidoWachsmuth.html">Guido Wachsmuth</a> (<span class="info">2</span> times)</li>
					<li><a href="../profile/VadimZaytsev.html">Vadim Zaytsev</a> (<span class="info">2</span> times)</li>
					<li><a href="../profile/AlpanaDubey.html">Alpana Dubey</a> (<span class="info">1</span> times)</li>
				</ul>

		</ul>

<h2>List of papers (8)</h2>
<ul>
<li><span class="info">(<a href="../atem2006s/index.html">ATEM 2006 SI</a>)</span> <em><a href="../atem2006s/paper04.html">Learning Context-Free Grammar Rules from a Set of Program</a></em> (<a href="../profile/AlpanaDubey.html">Alpana Dubey</a>, <a href="../profile/PankajJalote.html">Pankaj Jalote</a>, <a href="../profile/ShubhaniAggarwal.html">Shubhani Aggarwal</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The core task is inferring missing context-free grammar rules (grammar completion) from program samples and an approximate grammar.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t2a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It targets reverse engineering of dialect grammars when documentation/manuals are missing, i.e., recovery of language definitions.
">T2A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The approach is experimentally verified on multiple programming languages to demonstrate feasibility and effectiveness.
">T5E</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The inferred artefacts are CFG rules, i.e., meta-language objects used to define and generate parsers.
">T3A</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2009/index.html">SLE 2009</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2009/paper01.html">Language Evolution in Practice: The History of GMF</a></em> (<a href="../profile/MarkusHerrmannsdörfer.html">Markus Herrmannsdörfer</a>, <a href="../profile/DanielRatiu.html">Daniel Ratiu</a>, <a href="../profile/GuidoWachsmuth.html">Guido Wachsmuth</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The paper is explicitly about how the GMF language/tooling evolved over time and what that evolution looked like in practice.
">T2B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" GMF is a language workbench/tooling platform, so the narrative is grounded in evolution of meta-tools.
">T4A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t2a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It also concerns lifecycle aspects of a language framework (changes, migration, and long-term sustainability).
">T2A</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2011/index.html">SLE 2011</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2011/paper10.html">Reconstructing Complex Metamodel Evolution</a></em> (<a href="../profile/SanderDVermolen.html">Sander D. Vermolen</a>, <a href="../profile/GuidoWachsmuth.html">Guido Wachsmuth</a>, <a href="../profile/EelcoVisser.html">Eelco Visser</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The paper addresses metamodel evolution, a central maintenance problem in model-driven engineering.
">T2B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t2a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It focuses on recovery/reconstruction of evolution histories from existing artifacts.
">T2A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Reconstructing evolution implies deriving migration mappings/transformations between metamodel versions.
">T4B</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2012s/index.html">SLE 2012 SI</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2012s/paper03.html">A survey of grammatical inference in software engineering</a></em> (<a href="../profile/AndrewWStevenson.html">Andrew W. Stevenson</a>, <a href="../profile/JamesRCordy.html">James R. Cordy</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The paper surveys methods for inferring grammars from software artifacts, i.e., techniques for recovering and analysing language descriptions.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t2a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Grammatical inference is repeatedly discussed as a means for recovering undocumented or partially documented languages and formats from existing systems.
">T2A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The survey is grounded in formal language/automata theory and learning-theoretic results that underpin inference approaches.
">T5D</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL" title=" A substantial part of the surveyed application space concerns DSLs and other software languages whose grammars are inferred for engineering purposes.
">T3C</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2014/index.html">SLE 2014</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2014/paper04.html">Bounded Seas: Island Parsing Without Shipwrecks</a></em> (<a href="../profile/JanKurš.html">Jan Kurš</a>, <a href="../profile/MirceaLungu.html">Mircea Lungu</a>, <a href="../profile/OscarNierstrasz.html">Oscar Nierstrasz</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The core contribution is a parsing technique (island grammars) for robust/partial language processing.
">T5B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t2a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It supports error recovery and robust parsing when dealing with incomplete or noisy source input.
">T2A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3d.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The technique is motivated by practical manipulation of general-purpose programming language code.
">T3D</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2016/index.html">SLE 2016</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2016/paper20.html">Raincode Assembler Compiler (Tool Demo)</a></em> (<a href="../profile/VolodymyrBlagodarov.html">Volodymyr Blagodarov</a>, <a href="../profile/YvesJaradin.html">Yves Jaradin</a>, <a href="../profile/VadimZaytsev.html">Vadim Zaytsev</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t6b.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The motivation is practical legacy code migration needs typical of industrial contexts.
">T6B</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t4c.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It is a compiler toolchain for translating/compiling legacy assembler (HLASM) artifacts.
">T4C</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3d.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The work targets a general-purpose (albeit low-level) programming language: IBM’s High Level Assembler.
">T3D</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t2a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" It addresses legacy recovery/migration scenarios from assembler codebases.
">T2A</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2019/index.html">SLE 2019</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2019/keynote1.html">Software Language Engineering – 42 Frequently Asked Questions</a></em> (<a href="../profile/RalfLämmel.html">Ralf Lämmel</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t6d.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The keynote is an explicit cross-cutting positioning exercise (definitions, relations to CC/MDE/PLT, practice, education, “technological space”), i.e., synergy/agenda-setting.
">T6D</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t2a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" Multiple FAQ clusters directly address lifecycle questions (what’s the lifecycle of a software language; mission completion; long-term evolution of the field).
">T2A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t6b.html"><span class="tagL" title=" A significant slice is about SLE “in practice” (Big Tech needs, career profiles, organizational reality), grounded in an industrial vantage point.
">T6B</span></a></li><li><span class="info">(<a href="../sle2020/index.html">SLE 2020</a>)</span> <em><a href="../sle2020/paper09.html">Software Language Engineers’ Worst Nightmare</a></em> (<a href="../profile/VadimZaytsev.html">Vadim Zaytsev</a>) 
<a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagM" title=" The main contribution of the paper is to design a language called BabyCobol.
">T1A</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL" title=" BabyCobol is a domain-specific language.
">T3C</span></a>
<a href="../tag/t2a.html"><span class="tagL" title=" The domain for this language design experience is legacy software.
">T2A</span></a></li></ul>
